var html='<img src="//newspoverty.geolive.ca/localnewsresearch-logo.png" style="height: 56px; margin-right: 204px;">'+
    '<img src="//newspoverty.geolive.ca/geolive-logo.png"/>'+
    '<h3>The Local News Map: Tell us what\'s happening to local news in your community</h3>'+

    '<p>This crowd-sourced map tracks what is happening to local newspapers, broadcast outlets and online news sites in communities across Canada. It displays data going back to 2008, which marked the beginning of a deep recession and a turning point for many previously profitable local news organizations.</p>'+

    '<p>For the purposes of this project, a local news outlet is defined as a news organization that maintains independence from those it covers, demonstrates a commitment to accuracy/transparency, and is devoted primarily to reporting and publishing timely, originally-produced news about local people, places, issues and events in a defined geographic area. The markers that users add to the map display information about about changes to local news ecosystems including:'+

    '<ul><li>The closing, launch or merger of a news outlet (radio, television, online, or newspaper)</li>'+
    '<li>Service increases such as increased publication frequency for a community paper, or the addition of a local newscast/public affairs show by a local radio/television station</li>'+
    '<li>Service reductions such as a broadcaster’s decision to cancel/reduce the length of a local newscast, or a reduction in the number of times a newspaper publishes per week</li>'+
    '</ul></p>'+

    '<p>Limitations:'+

    '<ul><li>The map does not track layoffs/hiring by local news organizations that continue to operate</li>'+
    '<li>Changes to local magazines are not tracked primarily because they tend to appear monthly and don’t tend to be as focused on timely, local news. Having said that, the map design is iterative, so a magazine layer could be added in the future</li>'+
    '<li>We endeavor to ensure the map’s accuracy by moderating the content of new markers and by ensuring that the information for each marker includes a link to source material. This is, however, a crowd-sourced tool, so it is constantly being updated and revised</li>'+
    '</ul></p>'+

    '<p>About this project: This project is the result of a collaboration between Professor <a href="http://rsj.journalism.ryerson.ca/team/april-lindgren/" target="_blank">April Lindgren</a>, lead investigator for the <a href="http://localnewsresearchproject.ca/" target="+blank">Local News Research Project</a> at Ryerson University’s School of Journalism and Associate Professor <a href="http://joncorbett.com/JonCorbett/Home.html" target="_blank">Jon Corbett</a>, who leads the University of British Columbia’s <a href="http://spice.geolive.ca/" target="_blank">SpICE Lab</a> (Spatial Information for Community Mapping). It was created with financial support'+
    ' <a href="http://geothink.ca/" target="_blank">Canadian Geospatial and Open Data Research Partnership;</a> Canadian Media Guild/CWA Canada; Canadian Journalists for Free Expression; a Mitacs Accelerate grant;  Unifor;  and Ryerson University.</p>'+
    '<p>Contact us: <a href="mailto:localnewspoverty@gmail.com" target="_blank">localnewspoverty@gmail.com</a></p>';


